hands_on_practices.solution:
Each qubit is an independent Bernoulli trial with success (excited) probability $p=\frac{1}{3}$. Let $X$ be the number of excited qubits among $n=4$ qubits. Then $X$ follows a binomial distribution with parameters $(n,p)$, and the probability of exactly $k=2$ successes is
$$
\Pr(X=2)=\binom{4}{2}p^{2}(1-p)^{4-2}.
$$
Substituting $p=\frac{1}{3}$ gives
$$
\Pr(X=2)=\binom{4}{2}\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^{2}\left(1-\frac{1}{3}\right)^{2}
=6\cdot\frac{1}{9}\cdot\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^{2}
=6\cdot\frac{1}{9}\cdot\frac{4}{9}
=\frac{24}{81}
=\frac{8}{27}.
$$
Therefore, the probability is $\frac{8}{27}$.
